Title: \text{The Chain Rule}
Side_1: \text{ Given } Z = Z(x(t),y(t)) \text{ the chain rule allows us to evaluate } \frac{dZ}{dt} \text{ as }
Side_2: \frac{dZ}{dt} = \left(\frac{\partial Z}{\partial x\right)\left(\frac{d x}{dt\right) + \left(\frac{\partial Z}{\partial y\right)\left(\frac{d Z}{dy\right)

Title: \text{The Chain Rule : Example }
Side_1: \test{ Given } Z = e^{xy} - x\sin(y) \text{ where } x = 3t^2-t \text{ and } y = e^{3t^2} \text{ determine } \frac{dZ}{dt}
Side_2: \frac{dZ}{dt} = \left( ye^{xy} - \sin(y)\right)\left(6t-1\right) + \left(xe^{xy} - x\cos(y)\right)\left(6te^{3t^2}\right)

Title: \text{The Partial Chain Rule}
Side_1: \text{ Given } Z = Z(x(s,t),y(s,t)) \text{ the chain rule allows us to evaluate } \frac{\partial Z}{\partial s} \text{ as }
Side_2: \frac{\partial Z}{\partial s} = \left(\frac{\partial Z}{\partial x\right)\left(\frac{\partial x}{\partial s\right) + \left(\frac{\partial Z}{\partial y\right)\left(\frac{\partial Z}{\partial s\right)

Title: \text{The Partial Chain Rule : Example }

Title: \text{The Chain Rule : Implicit Differentiation }
Side_1: \text{ Given } F(x,y,Z(x,y)) = 0 \text{ we can evaluate } \frac{\partial Z }{\partial x} \text{ and } \frac{\partial Z}{\partial y} \text{ as }
Side_2: \frac{\partial Z }{\partial x } = - \frac{ \frac{\partial F}{\partial x}}{ \frac{\partial F}{\partial Z} } \text{ and } \frac{\partial Z }{\partial y } = - \frac{ \frac{\partial F}{\partial y}}{ \frac{\partial F}{\partial Z} }

Title: \text{ Double Integrals Over Rectangular Regions }
Side_1:
\text{ If we are evaluating } \int_a^b{\int_c^d{ f(x,y) dx}dy} \text{ where }

f(x,y) = g(x) h(y) \text{ then }
Side_2:
Because we have constant limits of integration and because the function is "multiplicatively seperable"

\int_a^b{\int_c^d{ f(x,y) dx}dy}  = \int_a^b h(y)dy \int_c^d g(x)dx

Title: \text{ Double Integral Over Rectangular Region : Example
Side_1: \text{ Evaluate } \int_0^1\int_2^3 x sin(xy) dydx
Side_2: \int_0^1\int_2^3 x sin(xy) dydx = \int_0^1 \left. \left[ - \cos(xy)\right]\right|_{y=2}^{y=3} = \int_0^1 \left( -\cos(3x) + \cos(2x) \right) = \left.\left[ (-1/3)\sin(3x) + (1/2)\sin(2x)\right]\right|_0^1=(1/2)\sin(2) - (1/3)\sin(3)

Title: \text{ Double Integrals that
Side_1: \text{ Evaluate } \int_0^1\int_2^3 e^{x} \cos(y) dxdy
Side_2: \text{ Evaluate } \int_0^1\int_2^3 e^{x} \cos(y) dxdy = \int_0^1 \cos(y)dy \int_2^3 e^xdx = \sin(y)|_0^1 e^x|_2^3 = \sin(1)\left(e^3 - e^2\right)

Title: \text{ Double Integrals with General Regions }
Side_1: \text{ General Process for integrating with functional boundaries is }

Title: \text{ Double integrals with General Regions : Example }
Side_1: \text{ Evaluate } \iint_R (2xy)dA \text{ where the region R is bounded by } y = \sqrt{x}, x = 1, y = 0
Side_2:
\text{ 1. The region is in the first quadrant bounded below by the x axis, to the right by x = 1 and above by } y = \sqrt{x}

\text{ 2. There's no benefit to do one order over the other, we can do it both ways.

\text{ 3. If y first, } 0 \le y \le \sqrt{x} \Rightarrow 0 \le x \le 1 \text{ and if did x first } y^2 \le x \le 1 \Rightarrow 0 \le y \le 1

\text{ 3. \int_0^1\int_0^{\sqrt{x}} 2xy dydx = \int_0^1 xy^2|_{y=0}^{y=\sqrt{x}} = \int_0^1 x^2 = (1/3)x^3|_0^1 = 1/3 \text{ OR } \int_0^1\int_{y^2}^1 (2xy)dxdy = \int_0^1 x^2 y|_{x=y^2}^{x=1}dy=\int_0^1 y(1-y^4)dy = (1/2)y^2 - (1/6)y^2 |0^1 = 1/2 - 1/6 = 2/6 = 1/3

Title: \text{ Double Integrals in Polar Coordinates }
Side_1: \text{ General Guidelines for Polar Coordinate Integration }

Title: \text{ Double Integrals in Polar : Example }
Side_1:
\text{ Evaluate the following integral via changing to polar coordinates }

\int_0^{\sqrt{2}} \ints_y^{\sqrt{ 4 - y^2 }}  xydxdy
Side_2:
\text{ 1. The region of integration is an eighth of a circle of radius 2 measured out from the x axis and has an angle of measure of } \pi/4

\text{ 2.  Limits of integration } 0 \le \theta \le \pi/4 \text{ and } 0 \le r \le 2

\text{ 3. Integrand : }xy = (r\cos(\theta))(r\sin(\theta)) = r^2 \sin(\theta)\cos(\theta)

\text{ 4. Differential Element } dxdy = dA = rdrd\theta

\text{ 5. Integrate } \int_0^2 \int_0^{\pi/4} r^3 \sin(\theta)\cos(\theta) d\theta dr = \int_0^2 r^3 dr \int_0^{\pi/4} \sin(\theta) \cos(\theta)d\theta = (1/4)r^4|_0^2 (1/2)\sin^2(\theta)|_0^{\pi/4} = (4)((1/2)(\sqrt{2}/2 = \sqrt{2}
